#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/types.rst:4
msgid "Typing in pytest"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/types.rst:7
msgid ""
"This page assumes the reader is familiar with Python's typing system and its "
"advantages."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/types.rst:9
msgid ""
"For more information, refer to `Python's Typing Documentation <https://docs."
"python.org/3/library/typing.html>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/types.rst:12
msgid "Why type tests?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/types.rst:14
msgid "Typing tests provides significant advantages:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/types.rst:16
msgid ""
"**Readability:** Clearly defines expected inputs and outputs, improving "
"readability, especially in complex or parameterized tests."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/types.rst:18
msgid ""
"**Refactoring:** This is the main benefit in typing tests, as it will "
"greatly help with refactoring, letting the type checker point out the "
"necessary changes in both production and tests, without needing to run the "
"full test suite."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/types.rst:20
msgid ""
"For production code, typing also helps catching some bugs that might not be "
"caught by tests at all (regardless of coverage), for example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/types.rst:22
msgid ""
"def get_caption(target: int, items: list[tuple[int, str]]) -> str:\n"
"    for value, caption in items:\n"
"        if value == target:\n"
"            return caption"
msgstr ""
"def get_caption(target: int, items: list[tuple[int, str]]) -> str:\n"
"    for value, caption in items:\n"
"        if value == target:\n"
"            return caption"

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/types.rst:30
msgid ""
"The type checker will correctly error out that the function might return "
"`None`, however even a full coverage test suite might miss that case:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/types.rst:32
msgid ""
"def test_get_caption() -> None:\n"
"    assert get_caption(10, [(1, \"foo\"), (10, \"bar\")]) == \"bar\""
msgstr ""
"def test_get_caption() -> None:\n"
"    assert get_caption(10, [(1, \"foo\"), (10, \"bar\")]) == \"bar\""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/types.rst:38
msgid ""
"Note the code above has 100% coverage, but the bug is not caught (of course "
"the example is \"obvious\", but serves to illustrate the point)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/types.rst:43
msgid "Using typing in test suites"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/types.rst:45
msgid ""
"To type fixtures in pytest, just add normal types to the fixture functions "
"-- there is nothing special that needs to be done just because of the "
"`fixture` decorator."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/types.rst:47
msgid ""
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture\n"
"def sample_fixture() -> int:\n"
"    return 38"
msgstr ""
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture\n"
"def sample_fixture() -> int:\n"
"    return 38"

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/types.rst:56
msgid ""
"In the same manner, the fixtures passed to test functions need be annotated "
"with the fixture's return type:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/types.rst:58
msgid ""
"def test_sample_fixture(sample_fixture: int) -> None:\n"
"    assert sample_fixture == 38"
msgstr ""
"def test_sample_fixture(sample_fixture: int) -> None:\n"
"    assert sample_fixture == 38"

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/types.rst:63
msgid ""
"From the POV of the type checker, it does not matter that `sample_fixture` "
"is actually a fixture managed by pytest, all it matters to it is that "
"`sample_fixture` is a parameter of type `int`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/types.rst:66
msgid ""
"The same logic applies to :ref:`@pytest.mark.parametrize <@pytest.mark."
"parametrize>`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/types.rst:68
msgid ""
"@pytest.mark.parametrize(\"input_value, expected_output\", [(1, 2), (5, 6), "
"(10, 11)])\n"
"def test_increment(input_value: int, expected_output: int) -> None:\n"
"    assert input_value + 1 == expected_output"
msgstr ""
"@pytest.mark.parametrize(\"input_value, expected_output\", [(1, 2), (5, 6), "
"(10, 11)])\n"
"def test_increment(input_value: int, expected_output: int) -> None:\n"
"    assert input_value + 1 == expected_output"

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/types.rst:76
msgid ""
"The same logic applies when typing fixture functions which receive other "
"fixtures:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/types.rst:78
msgid ""
"@pytest.fixture\n"
"def mock_env_user(monkeypatch: pytest.MonkeyPatch) -> None:\n"
"    monkeypatch.setenv(\"USER\", \"TestingUser\")"
msgstr ""
"@pytest.fixture\n"
"def mock_env_user(monkeypatch: pytest.MonkeyPatch) -> None:\n"
"    monkeypatch.setenv(\"USER\", \"TestingUser\")"

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/types.rst:86
msgid "Conclusion"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/types.rst:88
msgid ""
"Incorporating typing into pytest tests enhances **clarity**, improves "
"**debugging** and **maintenance**, and ensures **type safety**. These "
"practices lead to a **robust**, **readable**, and **easily maintainable** "
"test suite that is better equipped to handle future changes with minimal "
"risk of errors."
msgstr ""
